@node MAIN "Welcome to MDMaster, or CrAnKiN' wId' aReXxMaSTaHKOnTrOLLa!"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

Note: This guide uses "WordWrap," so resize away!

MDMaster is a control program to easily access your ARexx scripts for Vapor's MicroDot-2 Email/News program.  It was initially designed simply to outsmart the "bug" from MicroDot's pull-down ARexx menu.  However, it uses the really nifty RexxTricks.library viewlist function, so it has the capacity to search for a particular arexx script.  Therefore, if you have several scripts (though, I don't know of too many), it has added value.

MDMaster is not for those people who have only ONE ARexx script in MicroDot's REXX directory, as this script will only add overhead.  In other words, if you only have one ARexx script (like the MD2V), why bother?


   @{"  Requirements     " link NEEDS} :  What does it need?

   @{"  Installing       " link INSTALL} :  Okay, how do I make it work?

   @{"  Un-installing    " link REMOVE} :  If you don't like it.

   @{"  Usage            " link USAGE} :  How do I use it?

   @{"  Mumbo-Jumbo      " link LEGAL} :  Two parts bat-wing... (legal stuff)

   @{"  Distribution     " link DISTRO} :  Yup, free.

   @{"  Kudos and Thanks " link THANKS} :  Who-dunnit, and who helped.

   @{"  BEEP             " BEEP} : Just a Beep!

   @{"  FAQ              " link FAQ} : Questions and Answers.
                                  






@endnode
@node NEEDS "Requirements"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

Requirements:

MDMaster is for use with MicroDot-2 from VaporWare, it will likely not work for any other mailer.  However, if you use another e-mail program and wish to see it ported, please feel free to email the author (Targhan@amiga.org).

MDMaster also needs the library RexxTricks (by JÜrgen Kohrmeyer) to be installed on your system.  Chances are that you already have this fine library for your Amiga, but if you don't--it's available on the Aminet.

The RexxMast program must be started with your system, but you already knew that.  (check wbstartup and S:user-startup)

You will need to make an additional directory for your MD associated ARexx scripts, and to move those scripts into that directory. (See the @{"installation" link INSTALL} section)

And that, as they say, is that.

@endnode
@node INSTALL "Set up"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

After ensuring that you have the RexxMast program in your startup and that you have RexxTricks.library installed, you can set up MDMaster.

Set up is fairly painless, and no install script is needed.

1. You'll need a new directory in your Microdot2 drawer named "MDRexx".

2. @{b}Move@{ub} all of your MicroDot related ARexx scripts into this new directory.
  a) SendBrowser.rexx (mdrx??) does not get moved.  Leave it be if you use this script.

3. Copy MDMaster.mdrx into MicroDot's original "REXX" directory.

4. You may want to copy this guide into Microdot's directory, just in case you want to read over how to put everything back the way it was.

 @{BPEN 10}@{fg shine}       Notes               @{fg text}@{BPEN 0}

 @{APEN 13}@{BPEN 12}  @{b}Note #1@{ub}  @{APEN 1}@{BPEN 0}

 If you don't want MDMaster to use the exit requester when canceling the action, then edit the following line within the MDMaster.mdrx script:

 @{BPEN 1}  @{b}@{fg fill}UseExitMessage = 1@{fg text}  @{fg shine}/* Change number to disable exit message */@{fg text} @{ub}  @{BPEN 0}

 Simply change the numerical value to any other integer ( 0, 2, 5, whatever ).  This will make MDMaster exit quietly on a cancelled action.

 @{APEN 14}@{BPEN 13}  @{b}Note #2@{ub}  @{APEN 1}@{BPEN 0}

 If you use a public screen different that Workbench (the default), then you will want to edit the following line inside MDMaster.mdrx:

 @{BPEN 1}  @{b}@{fg fill} NamedScreen = 'Default'  @{fg shine}/* Use your PubScreen Name if desired     */ @{fg text} @{BPEN 0} @{ub}

 Replace "Default" by the name of the public screen used by MicroDot, keeping the single quotes around the name.  This will have the viewlist window appear on the same screen as MicroDot, instead of workbench.

 @{BPEN 10}@{fg shine}       End of Notes        @{fg text}@{BPEN 0}


Finally, after completing the above, just close and restart MicroDot-2.  Doing that will allow MicroDot to re-scan the REXX directory, putting MDMaster into the ARexx menu.

@{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}

No exit requestor is desired, and MicroDot runs on the Voyager (© Oliver Wagner) public screen, appropriatly named "MUI_Screen".  If you don't want the WorkBench screen to pop-to-front, then you should disable the exit-message.

@{bpen 1}   @{b}@{fg fill}UseExitMessage = 0          @{fg text}  @{fg shine}   /* Change number to disable exit message  */@{fg text}@{ub} @{bpen 0}
@{bpen 1}   @{b}@{fg fill}NamedScreen = 'MUI_Screen'     @{fg text}  @{fg shine}/* Use your PubScreen Name if desired     */@{fg text} @{ub}@{bpen 0}


Important: If you have any buttons linking to an ARexx script in the original REXX directory of Microdot2, then you will need to edit your preferences to point the button to the scripts new abode.



@endnode
@node REMOVE "Ay Ay, yeah, good-bye.  Na-na, NAH-NAH... GoodBye!"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

If you don't need MDMaster anymore...

Delete MDMaster.mdrx from MD's REXX directory, copy everything from MDRexx to Rexx, delete MDRexx, close Microdot, restart microdot, and adjust your preferences accordingly.

Couldn't be simpler, no?

@endnode
@node USAGE "How do I ______ ?"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

Using MDMaster is fairly simple.

1. Initiating MDMaster.

  a) if installed properly, MDMaster.mdrx should be seen from Microdot's pull down menu, under the "ARexx" heading.
  b) if the user desires, a button could be assigned from Microdot's preferences to launch MDMaster. (See Microdot documentation)
  c) please note, if you need a message highlighted for a script to work--then it needs to be highlighted before selecting the "Launch" button from the lister window.


2. Using the Lister.

  a) The "Select" lister has a list of scripts found, an input string gadget, and three buttons.

     1) Use the TAB key to quickly change highlighting from one gadget to another.

  b) The list:

     1) A list of ARexx scripts that can be launched, multi-select is turned OFF, so only one of the scripts can be hilighted.
     2) Use the ARROW keys or the mouse to select a script.

  c) Searching:

     1) The text field and search button allows you to quickly locate the script you are looking to use.
     2) Type the name you wish to find in the text-string, and click on "Search", this will not activate the script--only highlight it.
     3) The search field supports the Amiga wildcard system, i.e. "#?"

   d) The launch button activates the selected script.

     1) If no script is selected, the program acts as if the "Cancel" button was pressed, and the window closes.

   e) Using the "Cancel" button pops up a requester telling the user that he, or she, has aborted.  This is so that
      you will know that the script ended successfully, and has not bombed.

 @{APEN 11}@{BPEN 10}  @{b}Note!@{ub}  @{APEN 1}@{BPEN 0}

 See the @{"Installation Section" link INSTALL} to configure the ViewList screen option and the cancel-requestor option.




@endnode

@node FAQ "FAQ"
 @{APEN 10}@{bg text}  @{b}@{u} MDMaster @{uu}: The Microdot Master ARexx Control Program   @{ub}@{APEN 1}@{bg back}

A spiffy bug work around for MicroDot-2's ARexx bug, and a nifty way to select from several MD specific ARexx scripts.

@{b}MDMaster ©2002 David Crawford@{ub}
@{b}@{APEN 9}-----------------------------@{APEN 1}@{ub}

FAQ:

@{fg text}@{b}Q. How does MDMaster know where to look for my scripts?@{ub} @{fg text}

A. It uses Microdot's ENV variable.

--

@{b}Q. My lister window is empty, why?@{ub}

A. You don't have any arexx (.mdrx, or .rexx) scripts in your MDRexx directory.

--

@{b}Q. When I start MDMaster, all I get is a shell window saying, "Error reading directory."  What gives?  @{ub}

A. You never made the MDRexx directory.

--

@{b}Q. It don't work! @{ub}

A. Start RexxMast!

--

@{b}Q. Why did you bother?@{ub}

A. It was fun :-P


@endnode
